images.alt:
Analysis Overview

The PDF "2025-National-Security-Strategy.pdf.pdf" is the "National Security Strategy of the United States of America, November 2025," spanning about 65,000 characters, structured into chapters like Introduction, Wants, Means, and Strategy (Principles, Priorities, Regions). It exhibits stylistic uniformity with repetitive phrases ("America First," "President Trump's," "we want"), long sentences, and conservative rhetoric—typical of official strategy documents but featuring hallmarks like error-free text and high coherence suggestive of LLM assistance. No explicit author names; likely contributors include Trump Administration figures (e.g., advisors like Stephen Miller), evident from Trump-specific praise.

Author Differences

Paragraphs show minimal stylistic variations: rhetorically political sections (e.g., Trump praise) feel more personal/human with idiomatic turns ("suck us into conflicts"), while technical/regional parts (e.g., Asia economics) are precise and list-like—indicating 2–3 authors: a rhetorician (Trump-aligned) and policy experts. "President Trump's Necessary, Welcome Correction" (p. 2) and "Principles" (pp. 8–11) have dramatic, narrative flair ("new golden age," "President of Peace" with fictional 2025 peace deals), fitting a lead author. Regional sections vary in tone: aggressive in Western Hemisphere ("Trump Corollary," pp. 15–19), more reflective in Europe ("civilizational self-confidence," p. 25).
​

Under the assumption that fictional elements are deliberate exaggerations or falsehoods intentionally added or retained by human authors, LLM probability decreases across narrative and principles sections. Such insertions reflect purposeful political rhetoric typical of Trump-aligned drafters (e.g., hyperbole, like "new golden age"), not AI hallucinations, as humans would strategically embed them for messaging. Repetitive, generic lists remain high-LLM indicators due to uniform, low-variability structure (e.g., endless "we want" enumerations), likely AI-drafted for efficiency then human-edited.

High LLM probability (>80%) persists only in formulaic, descriptive passages lacking creative flair: "What Do We Want Overall?" (pp. 3–5) with predictable prosperity/military lists; "Priorities" subpoints (pp. 11–15, e.g., migration, trade rebalancing) featuring neutral, bullet-like phrasing ("critical supply chains," "reindustrialization"). Narrative polemics ("How American Strategy Went Astray," p. 1; Trump corrections, p. 2) and principles (pp. 8–11) signal stronger human authorship, as intentional fictions align with rhetorical style over AI neutrality. Regional specifics (Asia economics, pp. 19–24; Europe, pp. 25–27) mix expert input with possible AI outlines, but human oversight is evident in tailored aggression.​

What exactly do we do?

We make AI do the dishes, so directors can focus on the main course: the craft, the story, and the performances.

At The Sweetshop, we use AI as a creative ally, never a crutch. It’s there to sharpen the work. That might mean building background plates, scaling crowd shots, or replacing generic stock with footage that feels shot-for-purpose. But only where it elevates the idea.

From the very first draft, we look for ways to shift time and budget back toward the beating heart of the film - performance, story, and craft. AI allows us to handle things like product swaps without reshoots, deliver translations and localisations that feel natural, and generate additional footage that blends seamlessly with what’s already been shot.

Most importantly, we stress-test early. Pre-production becomes our playground, where we prototype and iterate so that by the time we’re on set, the thinking is locked and the energy is high. Everyone, clients, directors, and editors, is aligned. Which means the shoot can be what it should be: focused, fun, and fully in service of the creative.

Here's what's going to happen next.
Somewhere, right now, a trans person is teaching a class, or coaching a team, or working at a library, or providing healthcare. They're doing their job. They're probably good at it. And at some point, someone is going to have a problem with them. Maybe a parent, maybe a student, maybe a coworker. The problem won't really be about job performance. The problem will be that they're trans.
That person, or someone connected to them, will take their grievance to social media. If they're lucky, Libs of TikTok will pick it up. Or Turning Point. Or one of the other accounts that have built massive followings by turning trans people into content. The post will frame the trans person as a predator, or a groomer, or a bully, or a tyrant. It won't matter what actually happened. The framing is the point.

Then the calls will start. To the school board, to the administration, to the HR department. Local news will cover the "controversy." A state legislator will demand an investigation. The institution, desperate to make the problem go away, will put the trans person on leave. Maybe they'll be fired outright. Maybe they'll resign because the harassment makes it impossible to do their job. Either way they're gone.
And then the person who started it all will go on Fox News. They'll get a GoFundMe. Maybe a speaking gig at a conservative conference. If the story is big enough, if it goes viral enough, they might get something more. A podcast. A book deal. A center with their name on it.
This is not a guess. This is a pattern. We've watched it happen over and over again, and we will keep watching it happen until the institutions that capitulate to these campaigns start recognizing them for what they are: coordinated attempts to purge trans people from public life, dressed up as individual controversies.
